    {
      "label": {
        "none": [
          "Historical Context"
        ]
      },
      "value": {
        "none": [
          "The Public Transportation Amendments of 1980 were proposed in response to growing concerns about traffic congestion, air quality, and the need for sustainable urban development. The legislation aimed to provide significant federal funding to enhance public transportation systems across the country. While there was some public support for improving transit options, there were also debates about funding priorities and the effectiveness of such investments. Ultimately, the amendments were enacted, leading to increased federal support for public transportation initiatives."
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "label": {
        "none": [
          "Completed"
        ]
      },
      "value": {
        "none": [
          "Complete"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "label": {
        "none": [
          "Notable Quotes"
        ]
      },
      "value": {
        "none": [
          "\"The direct consequences of this action would lead to a severe curtailment of mass transit services, the transfer of virtually impossible financial burdens to state and local governments, deterioration of existing equipment and service levels, significant losses in patronage, reduced progress or the complete abandonment of projects now under construction, and reduced or complete curtailment of planning for additional transportation projects.\" — Chapter II – Alternatives Including the Proposed Action",
          "\"The TEA also provides the necessary funding capabilities for the Department to respond to energy shortfall situations that would force a major diversion of people from their private automobiles to transit.\" — Comparison and Selection of Preferred Alternative"
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
